      • oneStudentResults

        public static java.lang.String oneStudentResults​(int studentId,
                                                 java.util.List<Course> courses)
        Construct a String describing a given student's labs for all courses. The format of the returned String should be similar to the following example:
        for Sophie Princess
        in course CSC251
        lab00 40 out of 50 for 80%
        lab01 81 out of 90 for 90%
        in course CSC258
        labSayHello 100 of 100 for 100%
        etc.
        Parameters:
        studentId - whose name, id number, courses and labs in each course is to be returned
        courses - list to search for the given studentId
        Returns:
        String formatted as above

      • createAssignment

        public static void createAssignment​(Course courseToHandle,
                                    java.lang.String assignmentName,
                                    int possiblePoints)
        Create a new Assignment for each student in the given Course.
        The application "should" ask the user
        "give me the grade for Sophie,
        now give me the grade for Sally,
        now give me the grade for Jack...."

        That's really too much pain and agony for our purposes, so we'll just assign a random grade for each student as we create the Assignment objects. The assigned grades will be 70% or higher for each person.

        Note that since assignments are identified by name, multiple attempts at an assignment (i.e., two assignments with the same name) are allowed.

        Parameters:
        courseToHandle - - the Assignments will be added to this Course
        assignmentName - - name for the new Assignment objects
        possiblePoints - - maximum number of points for these Assignment objects

      • populateCourse

        public static void populateCourse​(Course c,
                                  int seats)
        Add up to the given number of students to a given course.
        Note that since our Student generator can generate duplicate students, and since a Course will gracefully ignore adding duplicate students, less than the specified students may wind up being added to the course.
        Parameters:
        c - - Course for the new Students
        seats - - The number of students to be randomly generated and added to the course. See above why the course might actually wind up with fewer Students than this parameter specifies.
